message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient has symptoms of hypoglycemia and laboratory results showing elevated serum insulin and C-peptide levels. The negative sulfonylurea and IGF-2 tests suggest that it is not exogenous insulin or an insulinoma but most likely a beta cell tumor of the pancreas, such as an insulinoma. Heat stroke and an alpha cell tumor of the pancreas are not likely causes of these symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s blood glucose is low, but insulin and proinsulin levels are high. This, along with the negative results for sulfonylurea and IGF-2, suggests the most likely cause of the hypoglycemia is a beta cell tumor of the pancreas, also known as insulinoma. Heat stroke does not typically cause hypoglycemia, while exogenous insulin would result in a different pattern of insulin and proinsulin levels. Alpha cell tumors of the pancreas produce glucagon, which would result in hyperglycemia rather than hypoglycemia.
